mSettings so request-time reads come from the in-memory\nsettings snapshot instead of opening a Hibernate session. Health-check\nendpoints (e.g. /api/ping, /api/system/ping) and CORS preflight requests\nno longer depend on the database for whitelist lookups, and the dedicated\ncorsWhitelistCache is no longer needed.\n\nChanges:\n\n- SystemSettings: corsWhitelist accessor + parseCorsWhitelist /\n  encodeCorsWhitelist helpers (comma + newline tolerant on parse,\n  deterministic sorted comma-joined output on encode).\n- DhisCorsProcessor: reads from SystemSettingsProvider, dropped\n  ConfigurationService dependency.\n- CspFilter: same migration so the existing filter keeps working with\n  the new whitelist source until the CSP refactor PR replaces it.\n- ConfigurationController: getConfiguration overlays corsWhitelist from\n  settings for API compatibility; setCorsWhitelist writes via\n  settingsService.put with SystemSettings.encodeCorsWhitelist.\n- DefaultConfigurationService: removed isCorsWhitelisted; logic was\n  duplicated in DhisCorsProcessor.\n- Configuration.hbm.xml: removed the corsWhitelist set mapping. The\n  field stays on Configuration as an API-compat field only.\n- Idempotent Flyway migration V2_44_5 aggregates rows from\n  configuration_corswhitelist into systemsetting and drops the legacy\n  table; safe on replay and on empty source tables.\n- Removed CacheProvider.createCorsWhitelistCache and the corsWhitelistCache\n  Region; the in-memory SystemSettings snapshot is the new source of truth.\n\nTests: new DhisCorsProcessorTest, refreshed CspFilterTest for the new\nconstructor, ConfigurationServiceTest and ConfigurationControllerTest\nadjusted for the API-compat overlay.\n\nThis is a prerequisite for the CSP centralization PR which depends on\nSystemSettingsProvider-backed CORS reads in CspPolicyService.\n\nAI Assisted","author":{"name":"Morten Svanaes","email":"msvanaes@dhis2.org"},"id":"f6795cbe42f10b5782bd462fa1333f5139a01611","tree_id":"c0887902c7d